Docker Networking — Bridge, Host, None
Network Types at a Glance
Driver	Isolation	Use Case
bridge	Container ↔ Container via virtual switch	Default; microservices on same host
host	No isolation — shares host network stack	High-performance, low-latency workloads
none	Completely isolated, no network	Security sandboxing, batch jobs
overlay	Multi-host (Swarm/K8s)	Distributed systems
macvlan	Container gets its own MAC/IP	Legacy apps needing direct LAN access

Step-by-Step Hands-On Practice
Step 1 — Inspect Default Networks
# See all networks Docker creates by default
docker network ls

# Inspect the default bridge network
docker network inspect bridge

# Notice: "Subnet", "Gateway", connected containers

Step 2 — Understand the Default Bridge (and its limits)

# Start two containers on the default bridge
docker run -d --name app1 alpine sleep 3600
docker run -d --name app2 alpine sleep 3600

# Try to ping by NAME — this will FAIL on default bridge
docker exec app1 ping -c 2 app2
# ping: bad address 'app2'  ← no DNS on default bridge!

# But ping by IP works
APP2_IP=$(docker inspect -f '{{range.NetworkSettings.Networks}}{{.IPAddress}}{{end}}' app2)
docker exec app1 ping -c 2 $APP2_IP

# Cleanup
docker rm -f app1 app2
Key insight: Default bridge has no automatic DNS. Custom bridges do.

Step 3 — Create a Custom Bridge Network
# Create a custom bridge with explicit subnet
docker network create \
  --driver bridge \
  --subnet 192.168.100.0/24 \
  --gateway 192.168.100.1 \
  --opt com.docker.network.bridge.name=custom-br0 \
  my-app-network

# Verify
docker network inspect my-app-network

Step 4 — Connect Two Containers on Custom Network
# Start a backend (simulated with nginx)
docker run -d \
  --name backend \
  --network my-app-network \
  nginx:alpine

# Start a frontend that talks to backend
docker run -d \
  --name frontend \
  --network my-app-network \
  alpine sleep 3600

# Ping backend BY NAME — works because custom bridge has built-in DNS
docker exec frontend ping -c 3 backend

# Make an HTTP request from frontend to backend by name
docker exec frontend wget -qO- http://backend
# Returns nginx welcome page HTML ✓

Step 5 — Run a Real Two-Container App (App + DB)
# Create isolated network for this app
docker network create todo-net

# Start PostgreSQL
docker run -d \
  --name todo-db \
  --network todo-net \
  --env POSTGRES_PASSWORD=secret \
  --env POSTGRES_DB=todos \
  postgres:16-alpine

# Start a client that connects to DB by service name
docker run -it --rm \
  --network todo-net \
  postgres:16-alpine \
  psql -h todo-db -U postgres -d todos -c "\l"
# Lists databases — connected using hostname 'todo-db' ✓

Step 6 — Connect a Container to Multiple Networks]
docker network create frontend-net
docker network create backend-net

# DB only on backend-net (not exposed to frontend)
docker run -d --name db --network backend-net postgres:16-alpine

# API on both networks (acts as a bridge between tiers)
docker run -d --name api --network backend-net nginx:alpine
docker network connect frontend-net api

# Verify api has two IPs
docker inspect api --format '{{range $k,$v := .NetworkSettings.Networks}}{{$k}}: {{$v.IPAddress}}{{"\n"}}{{end}}'

# Cleanup
docker rm -f db api
docker network rm frontend-net backend-net

Step 7 — Host Network (Linux only)
# Container shares host's network stack directly
docker run -d --name host-nginx --network host nginx:alpine

# nginx now listens on HOST port 80 — no -p mapping needed!
curl http://localhost:80

# Verify: container has no isolated IP
docker inspect host-nginx --format '{{.NetworkSettings.IPAddress}}'
# Returns empty — it IS the host

docker rm -f host-nginx

Step 8 — None Network (Complete Isolation)
# No network interface except loopback
docker run -it --rm --network none alpine sh

# Inside container:
ip addr          # only 'lo' (loopback)
ping 8.8.8.8     # fails
wget google.com  # fails
exit

Step 9 — Disconnect & Clean Up Networks
# Disconnect a running container from a network
docker network disconnect my-app-network frontend

# Remove unused networks
docker network rm my-app-network todo-net

# Remove ALL unused networks at once
docker network prune -f

Step 10 — Docker Compose with Custom Networks (real-world pattern)
docker-compose.yml:
version: "3.9"

services:
  frontend:
    image: nginx:alpine
    networks:
      - public-net

  api:
    image: node:20-alpine
    command: sh -c "npx serve -l 3000"
    networks:
      - public-net    # reachable by frontend
      - private-net   # reachable by db

  db:
    image: postgres:16-alpine
    environment:
      POSTGRES_PASSWORD: secret
    networks:
      - private-net   # ONLY api can reach db, not frontend

networks:
  public-net:
    driver: bridge
  private-net:
    driver: bridge
    internal: true    # no external internet access

docker compose up -d
docker compose exec frontend ping api    # ✓
docker compose exec frontend ping db     # ✗ — network isolation working
docker compose down

Interview Questions & Answers
Conceptual
Q1: What is the default network driver in Docker?

bridge. Every container not explicitly assigned a network joins the default bridge network.

Q2: What's the difference between default bridge and a user-defined bridge?

User-defined bridges provide automatic DNS resolution by container name. Default bridge only allows communication by IP. User-defined bridges also provide better network isolation.

Q3: When would you use --network host?

When you need maximum network performance (no NAT overhead), such as monitoring agents (prometheus, node-exporter), or when the app needs to bind to a specific host port without port mapping. Only works on Linux.

Q4: What does internal: true do in a Compose network?

Blocks all external (outbound internet) traffic on that network. Containers can still talk to each other but cannot reach the internet — useful for databases and internal services.

Q5: Can a container be on multiple networks simultaneously?

Yes. Use docker network connect <network> <container> at runtime or define multiple entries under networks: in Compose. The container gets a separate IP per network.

Practical / Scenario-Based
Q6: Two containers can't talk to each other by name. How do you debug?

Check they're on the same user-defined network (docker inspect) — default bridge has no DNS
Verify with docker exec <c1> ping <c2-name>
Check if a firewall or iptables rule is blocking
Use docker network inspect <network> to confirm both containers are listed as members
Q7: A container needs to access the host machine's service (e.g., a DB on the host). How?

Use the special hostname host.docker.internal (Docker Desktop) or 172.17.0.1 (the host's docker0 bridge IP on Linux). Or use --network host if on Linux.

Q8: How do you expose a service only to other containers, not to the host?

Use expose (not ports) in Compose — it makes the port available on the container network but doesn't bind to the host. Or use an internal: true network.

Q9: What happens to containers when you delete a custom network?

Docker refuses to delete a network that has active endpoints (running containers connected to it). You must disconnect or stop containers first.

Q10: How does Docker implement bridge networking under the hood?

Docker creates a virtual bridge (docker0 or custom br-xxxx) in the Linux kernel. Each container gets a veth (virtual ethernet) pair — one end inside the container (eth0), one end attached to the bridge. iptables rules handle NAT for outbound traffic.

Security-Focused
Q11: Why should microservices use separate networks instead of one shared network?

Principle of least privilege. If one container is compromised, it can only reach containers on the same network. A frontend container should never be able to directly connect to a database.

Q12: Can containers on different networks communicate?

Not by default. A container would need to be explicitly connected to both networks (acting as a router), or traffic must go through a container that bridges both.

Q13: What are the security risks of --network host?

The container can bind to any host port, potentially conflicting with or intercepting host services. It bypasses Docker's network isolation entirely. Avoid in production unless absolutely necessary.

Quick Reference Cheatsheet
Task	Command
List networks	docker network ls
Create custom bridge	docker network create --driver bridge mynet
Run on specific network	docker run --network mynet ...
Connect running container	docker network connect mynet container
Disconnect container	docker network disconnect mynet container
Inspect network	docker network inspect mynet
Remove network	docker network rm mynet
Remove unused networks	docker network prune
Get container IP	docker inspect -f '{{range.NetworkSettings.Networks}}{{.IPAddress}}{{end}}' c1

